WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.874
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.748 --> 00:00:08.530
LAURA MURPHY: Ben Folds
is a singer, songwriter,

00:00:08.530 --> 00:00:10.960
multi-platinum selling artist.

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:14.470
He's also a TV and film star.

00:00:14.470 --> 00:00:18.460
He's done a number of things
outside of the music industry

00:00:18.460 --> 00:00:20.500
that he should be very proud of.

00:00:20.500 --> 00:00:21.670
He's a father.

00:00:21.670 --> 00:00:23.450
He's a photographer.

00:00:23.450 --> 00:00:25.330
He's also the
soundtrack of my youth.

00:00:25.330 --> 00:00:26.020
No big deal.

00:00:26.020 --> 00:00:27.440
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:28.270
My mom is here.

00:00:28.270 --> 00:00:29.200
You can ask her.

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:29.320
BEN FOLDS: Hey.

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:30.060
LAURA MURPHY: She knows.

00:00:30.060 --> 00:00:30.559
Yeah.

00:00:30.559 --> 00:00:32.780
So we're super excited
to have you here.

00:00:32.780 --> 00:00:33.530
Thank you so much.

00:00:33.530 --> 00:00:35.630
It's a giant honor to
have you at Google today.

00:00:35.630 --> 00:00:36.130
So--

00:00:36.130 --> 00:00:36.540
BEN FOLDS: Well, thank you.

00:00:36.540 --> 00:00:37.331
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah.

00:00:37.331 --> 00:00:38.560
Thank you.

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:41.752
So we're going to do this
a bit differently today.

00:00:41.752 --> 00:00:43.210
I know that most
of you in the room

00:00:43.210 --> 00:00:46.000
know that Ben has a performance
tonight at the Fillmore.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.250
So he's going to
reserve his voice.

00:00:48.250 --> 00:00:50.950
Hopefully, you win tickets
so you can go hear him.

00:00:50.950 --> 00:00:53.740
You have been completely
jam packed on this Fall

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:55.450
tour all the way
until, I think, I

00:00:55.450 --> 00:00:58.280
saw your last show is
going to be in Honolulu.

00:00:58.280 --> 00:00:59.570
So that may not be so bad.

00:00:59.570 --> 00:01:00.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:00.070 --> 00:01:02.020
But it's been a
pretty packed tour.

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:04.209
And it's called "The Paper
Airplane Request Tour."

00:01:04.209 --> 00:01:07.270
So I thought what we could do
is just start off with tell us

00:01:07.270 --> 00:01:08.570
why it's called that?

00:01:08.570 --> 00:01:13.990
BEN FOLDS: Well, the second
half of the show, the set,

00:01:13.990 --> 00:01:16.750
is requests.

00:01:16.750 --> 00:01:19.790
And instead of people
shouting the request,

00:01:19.790 --> 00:01:23.050
which is scary if
you're sitting on stage.

00:01:23.050 --> 00:01:23.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:24.650 --> 00:01:27.170
Close your eyes, you see
people with pitchforks.

00:01:27.170 --> 00:01:28.090
They sound angry.

00:01:28.090 --> 00:01:29.814
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:29.814 --> 00:01:31.230
Because you can't
understand this.

00:01:31.230 --> 00:01:34.090
And I just thought, oh, people
just make a paper airplane

00:01:34.090 --> 00:01:35.140
and throw that.

00:01:35.140 --> 00:01:37.000
So basically, I just
walk around the stage

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:38.807
and pick those up and play them.

00:01:38.807 --> 00:01:40.390
I mean, it didn't
occur to me how many

00:01:40.390 --> 00:01:45.310
songs that I had either written,
done, been involved with that

00:01:45.310 --> 00:01:46.930
might be on stage.

00:01:46.930 --> 00:01:49.780
So I brushed up on
a couple hundred,

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:51.880
and then I've got about
50 left that I just can't

00:01:51.880 --> 00:01:53.530
seem to crack at the moment.

00:01:53.530 --> 00:01:55.714
LAURA MURPHY: What's
one of those 50?

00:01:55.714 --> 00:01:57.070
BEN FOLDS: Oh.

00:01:57.070 --> 00:01:57.710
I don't know.

00:01:57.710 --> 00:01:59.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:59.080 --> 00:02:01.930
You know, stuff
like, there's songs

00:02:01.930 --> 00:02:05.920
that I would have never
thought to play on the piano

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:07.207
by myself is why, like--

00:02:07.207 --> 00:02:08.040
LAURA MURPHY: Right.

00:02:08.040 --> 00:02:10.690
BEN FOLDS: So I did a movie
called "Over the Hedge"

00:02:10.690 --> 00:02:12.130
for DreamWorks.

00:02:12.130 --> 00:02:13.660
It was a kids' movie.

00:02:13.660 --> 00:02:15.730
And the songs I wrote
for that, I never

00:02:15.730 --> 00:02:18.495
expected to come back
to haunt me in any way.

00:02:18.495 --> 00:02:19.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:19.890 --> 00:02:23.230
The songs make me think
of conference calls.

00:02:23.230 --> 00:02:23.935
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:23.935 --> 00:02:25.150
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah.

00:02:25.150 --> 00:02:27.370
BEN FOLDS: But,
yeah, so there's one

00:02:27.370 --> 00:02:32.320
of those that's just like
kind of cacophony, horns.

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:33.112
It's a kiddie song.

00:02:33.112 --> 00:02:34.778
I never thought about
playing it before.

00:02:34.778 --> 00:02:36.560
But it's in the book
in case someone asks.

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:36.990
LAURA MURPHY: OK.

00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:37.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:37.420 --> 00:02:38.840
BEN FOLDS: And
somebody yesterday

00:02:38.840 --> 00:02:40.940
asked for something I wrote
when I was 16 years old,

00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:41.980
which got on the internet.

00:02:41.980 --> 00:02:42.570
I didn't know.

00:02:42.570 --> 00:02:42.790
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:42.790 --> 00:02:43.080
So--

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:43.630
LAURA MURPHY: Wow.

00:02:43.630 --> 00:02:45.046
BEN FOLDS: I
couldn't remember it.

00:02:45.046 --> 00:02:46.704
LAURA MURPHY: Well
so on the flip side

00:02:46.704 --> 00:02:48.370
of that, what's been
your favorite song?

00:02:48.370 --> 00:02:49.900
Of all the paper
airplanes that have

00:02:49.900 --> 00:02:52.694
landed on the stage, what's
been your favorite song to play?

00:02:52.694 --> 00:02:53.860
BEN FOLDS: Oh, I don't know.

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:55.610
I don't really have
favorites of anything.

00:02:55.610 --> 00:02:56.318
LAURA MURPHY: Oh.

00:02:56.318 --> 00:02:57.280
Even of your own stuff?

00:02:57.280 --> 00:02:57.940
BEN FOLDS: No.

00:02:57.940 --> 00:02:59.320
Especially of my own stuff.

00:02:59.320 --> 00:03:00.730
I think I've got a block there.

00:03:00.730 --> 00:03:01.231
So, yeah.

00:03:01.231 --> 00:03:02.688
LAURA MURPHY: Well,
that's awesome.

00:03:02.688 --> 00:03:04.330
BEN FOLDS: I try
to be a fair dad.

00:03:04.330 --> 00:03:07.270
LAURA MURPHY: Well, so Ben is
really involved with his fans.

00:03:07.270 --> 00:03:09.330
He's huge into social media.

00:03:09.330 --> 00:03:12.010
And so what we thought we'd do
next is just kind of highlight

00:03:12.010 --> 00:03:15.924
some of the ways that Ben
outreaches to his fans.

00:03:15.924 --> 00:03:18.340
And what we'd love to do, since
we're on the topic of tour

00:03:18.340 --> 00:03:21.850
is can you talk to us a little
bit about the VIP experiences

00:03:21.850 --> 00:03:25.690
that you offer around soundcheck
before each of your shows?

00:03:25.690 --> 00:03:27.670
And why you do that?

00:03:27.670 --> 00:03:30.360
BEN FOLDS: Well, I
mean, quite honestly,

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:34.360
I do it because, you know,
if I'm going to tour,

00:03:34.360 --> 00:03:36.490
I want to make the
most of it, you know.

00:03:36.490 --> 00:03:40.780
I like touring fine, but
I also like being home.

00:03:40.780 --> 00:03:46.390
So it takes care of a whole
lot of stuff at once on tour.

00:03:46.390 --> 00:03:49.330
The normal-- I've been
approached about these a few

00:03:49.330 --> 00:03:52.560
times, and didn't really want to
do them, because the ideas of--

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:54.337
look at-- Bon Jovi is great.

00:03:54.337 --> 00:03:55.420
I think Bon Jovi is great.

00:03:55.420 --> 00:03:56.211
I'm not making fun.

00:03:56.211 --> 00:03:57.760
But the idea of
like, I think I'd

00:03:57.760 --> 00:04:01.450
seen Bon Jovi standing
and taking pictures

00:04:01.450 --> 00:04:03.000
with people for two hours.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.350
And I don't want to do that.

00:04:05.350 --> 00:04:10.310
But what we realized is we
could do something like a class.

00:04:10.310 --> 00:04:14.850
So what we do is something
called a master class.

00:04:14.850 --> 00:04:17.772
Not really a master class, but
it's almost a master class.

00:04:17.772 --> 00:04:19.230
And then I will
let people come up,

00:04:19.230 --> 00:04:21.089
if they want to play the
song, and we'll talk about it.

00:04:21.089 --> 00:04:21.899
That's fine.

00:04:21.899 --> 00:04:25.710
So it's like a
class for people who

00:04:25.710 --> 00:04:28.680
are of any age that want to
talk about, commiserate about,

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:32.940
where they are in music,
or music education.

00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:36.384
And we were bringing local
music teachers in to begin with,

00:04:36.384 --> 00:04:38.550
because I think if you're
going to talk about music,

00:04:38.550 --> 00:04:42.840
it's best to do it in
context of having learned it.

00:04:42.840 --> 00:04:46.079
Which, as a rock
musician, you're

00:04:46.079 --> 00:04:48.370
really supposed to put off
the idea that you rolled out

00:04:48.370 --> 00:04:51.130
of bed one day,
and smoked a joint,

00:04:51.130 --> 00:04:52.701
and started making up songs.

00:04:52.701 --> 00:04:53.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:57.020
And you know,
between that point,

00:04:57.020 --> 00:04:58.450
which is obvious that happened.

00:04:58.450 --> 00:04:59.875
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:01.300 --> 00:05:03.790
But at some point
you did learn it.

00:05:03.790 --> 00:05:08.177
I'm a big fan of as much formal
training as possible in music,

00:05:08.177 --> 00:05:09.760
no matter what kind
of music you make.

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:13.160
I think it makes it better.

00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:15.550
So that gives me a
chance to do that.

00:05:15.550 --> 00:05:18.700
It gives me a chance
to connect people

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:21.080
on things like National
Endowment for the Arts, which

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:25.150
was sort of tentatively was
up on the chopping block

00:05:25.150 --> 00:05:26.140
for a little while.

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:28.879
And, you know, stuff.

00:05:28.879 --> 00:05:29.670
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah.

00:05:29.670 --> 00:05:30.336
BEN FOLDS: Yeah.

00:05:30.336 --> 00:05:33.490
So the VIP, that makes
me feel good because I

00:05:33.490 --> 00:05:35.680
feel like I'm hearing
from a lot of teachers,

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:37.870
I'm talking to people,
we're talking about music,

00:05:37.870 --> 00:05:39.940
and it's not as much
of a celebrity affair.

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:40.960
LAURA MURPHY: Right.

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:43.460
BEN FOLDS: So it's given-- it's
been a good thing, you know.

00:05:43.460 --> 00:05:45.610
It's actually-- and
I'm working on--

00:05:45.610 --> 00:05:47.450
I think I'm writing a book.

00:05:47.450 --> 00:05:47.950
And--

00:05:47.950 --> 00:05:49.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:52.010
It seems that way.

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:53.800
I can't tell people
with a straight face

00:05:53.800 --> 00:05:55.145
I'm working on my memoirs.

00:05:55.145 --> 00:05:56.404
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:57.760 --> 00:06:00.980
But it's good for that
too, because talking

00:06:00.980 --> 00:06:04.220
to people about music all
the time, and of all ages,

00:06:04.220 --> 00:06:06.200
and where they're
coming from, and how

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:09.050
they're learning
it is helpful to me

00:06:09.050 --> 00:06:10.670
when I'm outlining
the things that I

00:06:10.670 --> 00:06:13.100
think are important
when you're cramming

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:14.919
the music in your head.

00:06:14.919 --> 00:06:15.710
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah.

00:06:15.710 --> 00:06:18.200
I think one of those
experiences is called

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:19.610
"Ask Me Anything" and then--

00:06:19.610 --> 00:06:20.420
BEN FOLDS: Almost anything.

00:06:20.420 --> 00:06:22.180
LAURA MURPHY: Almost
anything about music.

00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:22.560
BEN FOLDS: AMAA.

00:06:22.560 --> 00:06:23.470
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah.

00:06:23.470 --> 00:06:25.084
"Ask Me Almost
Anything About Music."

00:06:25.084 --> 00:06:25.750
BEN FOLDS: Yeah.

00:06:25.750 --> 00:06:28.124
LAURA MURPHY: So you've had
some really interesting folks

00:06:28.124 --> 00:06:28.700
come through.

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:30.830
Have you ever had anyone
that's blown you away,

00:06:30.830 --> 00:06:32.967
or been really
musically talented?

00:06:32.967 --> 00:06:33.800
BEN FOLDS: Oh, yeah.

00:06:33.800 --> 00:06:38.630
I think almost everybody
who has bothered to step up,

00:06:38.630 --> 00:06:41.390
play a song, has been
really impressive to me.

00:06:41.390 --> 00:06:42.550
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah.

00:06:42.550 --> 00:06:46.600
BEN FOLDS: And, yeah, and
sometimes-- a couple of days

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:50.050
ago, I was sort
of taunting a kid

00:06:50.050 --> 00:06:55.660
to write a song on the spot,
because they were wondering

00:06:55.660 --> 00:07:00.340
about-- every night of my
solo career just about,

00:07:00.340 --> 00:07:05.890
since like 2002, I've sort of
had to freestyle songs onstage.

00:07:05.890 --> 00:07:10.815
It's been a sort of
a tradition where--

00:07:10.815 --> 00:07:13.190
I was playing in Chicago and
we were making a live album.

00:07:13.190 --> 00:07:15.160
This guy goes, rock that bitch.

00:07:15.160 --> 00:07:16.740
Rock this bitch.

00:07:16.740 --> 00:07:19.120
And he just meant I wasn't
playing fast enough, or loud

00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:19.750
enough, or something.

00:07:19.750 --> 00:07:21.666
But we were making a
live album, and I made up

00:07:21.666 --> 00:07:23.860
a song called that for him.

00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:24.440
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:26.220
And that became popular.

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:27.470
So that it became a code word.

00:07:27.470 --> 00:07:29.010
People would ask for that.

00:07:29.010 --> 00:07:31.660
And I do it with
symphony orchestras

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:34.660
regularly, where I'll
freestyle a song,

00:07:34.660 --> 00:07:38.860
and then I'll dictate parts
that I hear in the orchestra.

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:41.260
And so, yeah, I was
trying to get the kid

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:45.520
to put him in that position.

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:48.490
Let him make something up,
because we can do that.

00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:49.990
LAURA MURPHY: That's awesome.

00:07:49.990 --> 00:07:51.050
So, OK.

00:07:51.050 --> 00:07:52.300
You're here at Google.

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:57.160
And we, beyond the
obvious search engine

00:07:57.160 --> 00:07:58.624
that I'm sure you
use sometimes--

00:07:58.624 --> 00:08:00.040
BEN FOLDS: I've
heard of it, yeah.

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:00.760
LAURA MURPHY:
You've heard of it?

00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:01.180
Yeah.

00:08:01.180 --> 00:08:01.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:03.904
We also own a little video
property called YouTube--

00:08:03.904 --> 00:08:04.570
BEN FOLDS: Yeah.

00:08:04.570 --> 00:08:07.270
LAURA MURPHY: So
knowing all of that,

00:08:07.270 --> 00:08:09.946
and knowing how involved
you are with your fans,

00:08:09.946 --> 00:08:12.320
can you talk to us a little
bit about digital technology,

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:16.060
and how you use it to keep
in touch with your fans?

00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:19.210
BEN FOLDS: To be
very honest, I think

00:08:19.210 --> 00:08:24.580
my fans have always been the
types who are very ahead.

00:08:24.580 --> 00:08:26.710
Always have been ahead.

00:08:26.710 --> 00:08:30.430
To the point where
in 1999 I was signing

00:08:30.430 --> 00:08:32.530
at least as many burned CDs.

00:08:32.530 --> 00:08:33.876
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:35.669 --> 00:08:37.549
And I was fine with that.

00:08:37.549 --> 00:08:40.240
And I think that, because
I've embraced however

00:08:40.240 --> 00:08:42.070
they want to be
excited about music--

00:08:42.070 --> 00:08:42.960
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah.

00:08:42.960 --> 00:08:44.560
BEN FOLDS: --and
open to it, it's

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:51.480
been really more of--
like now my management,

00:08:51.480 --> 00:08:53.830
he comes from politics.

00:08:53.830 --> 00:08:56.260
He doesn't know
anything about music.

00:08:56.260 --> 00:08:59.740
And he also comes
from social media.

00:08:59.740 --> 00:09:02.470
I personally have
been on Facebook

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:05.020
for a total of about
three minutes once.

00:09:05.020 --> 00:09:06.460
To check it out,
and that's back--

00:09:06.460 --> 00:09:07.690
LAURA MURPHY: This is
your Facebook page.

00:09:07.690 --> 00:09:07.930
BEN FOLDS: Yeah.

00:09:07.930 --> 00:09:08.290
LAURA MURPHY: In
case you wondered.

00:09:08.290 --> 00:09:08.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:08.600 --> 00:09:08.820
Yeah.

00:09:08.820 --> 00:09:09.670
It's right here.

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:11.320
BEN FOLDS: Well,
last time I did it,

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:13.175
people were sending me
emails about poking.

00:09:13.175 --> 00:09:14.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:14.130 --> 00:09:15.185
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah.

00:09:15.185 --> 00:09:16.810
BEN FOLDS: That's
how far back it goes.

00:09:16.810 --> 00:09:18.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:22.010
I do, you know, I do read
the news on my phone.

00:09:22.010 --> 00:09:22.881
LAURA MURPHY: OK.

00:09:22.881 --> 00:09:23.380
Good.

00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:23.650
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:23.650 --> 00:09:25.566
BEN FOLDS: I know that's
terrible, I just do--

00:09:25.566 --> 00:09:27.730
LAURA MURPHY: Do watch
a lot of YouTube?

00:09:27.730 --> 00:09:30.274
Do you use YouTube as a
resource for your music, or--

00:09:30.274 --> 00:09:30.940
BEN FOLDS: I do.

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:32.620
Especially, like,
you know, one thing

00:09:32.620 --> 00:09:35.230
is because I make up
a song every night,

00:09:35.230 --> 00:09:37.750
sometimes I want to
remember what it was.

00:09:37.750 --> 00:09:39.140
And people will always film it.

00:09:39.140 --> 00:09:39.640
So--

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:39.790
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah.

00:09:39.790 --> 00:09:40.300
BEN FOLDS: --I'll back.

00:09:40.300 --> 00:09:42.010
In fact, one time
it came in handy

00:09:42.010 --> 00:09:47.980
because had some guy being a
little bit of a jackass online,

00:09:47.980 --> 00:09:52.780
saying that I'd stolen this
song from some guy I've never

00:09:52.780 --> 00:09:53.640
heard of.

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:58.123
And he was kind of a famous,
like a comedian in the UK.

00:09:58.123 --> 00:10:00.420
And so everyone was jumping
on the bandwagon saying,

00:10:00.420 --> 00:10:03.560
oh, I thought Ben was better
than that, to steal a song.

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:05.320
And I'm like, I
don't even know--

00:10:05.320 --> 00:10:08.186
I didn't really want to click
on that song they said I stole.

00:10:08.186 --> 00:10:10.060
So I didn't even want
a record of ever having

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:11.820
heard this damn thing.

00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:13.660
Anyway, I realized,
oh, wait a minute.

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:16.780
I made that song up on
stage mostly in 2011,

00:10:16.780 --> 00:10:18.920
way before that guy had
his first record out.

00:10:18.920 --> 00:10:20.045
LAURA MURPHY: That's funny.

00:10:20.045 --> 00:10:21.441
BEN FOLDS: So I went on YouTube.

00:10:21.441 --> 00:10:21.940
Found it.

00:10:21.940 --> 00:10:24.250
Someone had posted it.

00:10:24.250 --> 00:10:26.410
And sent that to
the guy in the UK.

00:10:26.410 --> 00:10:27.396
He's like, OK.

00:10:27.396 --> 00:10:27.895
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:27.895 --> 00:10:31.480
Like, will you have a press
conference now for me?

00:10:31.480 --> 00:10:32.211
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:32.211 --> 00:10:32.710
Because--

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:33.130
LAURA MURPHY: Will
you set this straight?

00:10:33.130 --> 00:10:35.260
BEN FOLDS: --everyone
thinks I'm a thief.

00:10:35.260 --> 00:10:37.540
I've been smeared.

00:10:37.540 --> 00:10:39.340
LAURA MURPHY: That's awesome.

00:10:39.340 --> 00:10:43.720
Well, so sort of in the same
vein of digital technology,

00:10:43.720 --> 00:10:44.805
you have three children?

00:10:44.805 --> 00:10:45.430
BEN FOLDS: Mhm.

00:10:45.430 --> 00:10:49.720
LAURA MURPHY: And there's a
ton of folks here at Google

00:10:49.720 --> 00:10:52.420
who are also working parents.

00:10:52.420 --> 00:10:54.250
Do you allow screen time?

00:10:54.250 --> 00:10:58.840
Do your kids use digital
technology for music research,

00:10:58.840 --> 00:10:59.710
too?

00:10:59.710 --> 00:11:01.320
BEN FOLDS: They do.

00:11:01.320 --> 00:11:02.650
They live in it, you know?

00:11:02.650 --> 00:11:03.520
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah.

00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:07.210
BEN FOLDS: They went to
Waldorf School for a few years

00:11:07.210 --> 00:11:10.840
to wash them clean of it,
which I think is good, too.

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:12.790
I think a combination is good.

00:11:12.790 --> 00:11:16.720
Some time off I think
was really good for them.

00:11:16.720 --> 00:11:18.310
And then time on is good.

00:11:18.310 --> 00:11:19.530
I don't really--

00:11:19.530 --> 00:11:22.030
I think anything
can be addictive.

00:11:22.030 --> 00:11:26.830
And certainly with
kids, iPads and stuff

00:11:26.830 --> 00:11:32.090
like that can start to
seem to form an addiction.

00:11:32.090 --> 00:11:35.330
But you know, short of
that, it's really amazing,

00:11:35.330 --> 00:11:37.332
because they have
at their fingertips

00:11:37.332 --> 00:11:39.040
all this information
that we didn't have.

00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:43.570
And I think also they
learn pretty quickly how

00:11:43.570 --> 00:11:49.760
to discern fake information, or
invalid information, I'd rather

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:51.200
not use the word fake anymore.

00:11:51.200 --> 00:11:52.480
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:52.480 --> 00:11:55.440
Invalid information
from valid information,

00:11:55.440 --> 00:11:58.540
where my generation
wasn't ready for it.

00:11:58.540 --> 00:12:00.810
We're like, whoa,
look at all that.

00:12:00.810 --> 00:12:04.200
And I think, you know,
also like, you know,

00:12:04.200 --> 00:12:05.400
e-mails, and things.

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.950
Like, they kind of
know how to do that

00:12:07.950 --> 00:12:09.090
without getting in trouble.

00:12:09.090 --> 00:12:12.570
There was a moment
in the Waldorf class

00:12:12.570 --> 00:12:17.050
one year where two of the
kids had gotten on Instagram.

00:12:17.050 --> 00:12:18.939
And they weren't supposed
to even be on it.

00:12:18.939 --> 00:12:20.730
But they had gotten on
it, and were calling

00:12:20.730 --> 00:12:22.560
each other horrible names.

00:12:22.560 --> 00:12:23.900
I mean, stuff that--

00:12:23.900 --> 00:12:29.435
I mean, look, I've said a
few bad words in my day.

00:12:29.435 --> 00:12:31.560
I can't repeat the kind of
things they were saying.

00:12:31.560 --> 00:12:32.310
LAURA MURPHY: Wow.

00:12:32.310 --> 00:12:34.200
BEN FOLDS: They were so gross.

00:12:34.200 --> 00:12:36.700
The teacher had them.

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:39.060
She printed it out,
as if it was a play.

00:12:39.060 --> 00:12:40.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:45.470
And had them read it aloud
into each other's face

00:12:45.470 --> 00:12:48.090
in front of the class.

00:12:48.090 --> 00:12:48.840
LAURA MURPHY: Wow.

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:51.080
BEN FOLDS: And they
would say, well,

00:12:51.080 --> 00:12:56.600
your mother is a f-ing B that
likes to cram Ds in her--

00:12:56.600 --> 00:12:57.640
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:57.640 --> 00:13:00.960
And you're like, wow.

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:05.180
And the teacher is like, I
don't think that's what it said.

00:13:05.180 --> 00:13:06.830
Well, it said
something like that.

00:13:06.830 --> 00:13:09.950
Well you're sitting
in front of him.

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:11.210
You say to him.

00:13:11.210 --> 00:13:13.400
And that's what you're doing
when you put it online.

00:13:13.400 --> 00:13:16.020
I think kids learn those things.

00:13:16.020 --> 00:13:17.750
And so it's a different era.

00:13:17.750 --> 00:13:20.027
I think in almost any
time-- the danger is talking

00:13:20.027 --> 00:13:21.860
about it for someone
like me is because I've

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:23.910
been through all the eras.

00:13:23.910 --> 00:13:25.940
And I think that
naturally we're all

00:13:25.940 --> 00:13:28.730
programmed to think
that new technology has

00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:31.340
some evil into the
world component to it.

00:13:31.340 --> 00:13:33.170
It's like everything
that was ever

00:13:33.170 --> 00:13:35.090
invented that was ever
important was just

00:13:35.090 --> 00:13:38.090
a sign that the end was near.

00:13:38.090 --> 00:13:39.570
And that's the way
our brains work.

00:13:39.570 --> 00:13:42.860
So I sort of got out
of that business.

00:13:42.860 --> 00:13:45.950
And I understand--
I'm not a total idiot.

00:13:45.950 --> 00:13:47.240
There's an electric piano.

00:13:47.240 --> 00:13:47.707
LAURA MURPHY: Oh.

00:13:47.707 --> 00:13:48.206
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:48.206 --> 00:13:49.110
I love that.

00:13:49.110 --> 00:13:51.270
BEN FOLDS: So what
do I think of those.

00:13:51.270 --> 00:13:53.550
LAURA MURPHY: Yeah,
that's awesome.

00:13:53.550 --> 00:13:54.050
All right.

00:13:54.050 --> 00:13:57.777
Well, we're going to focus
on something else you love.

00:13:57.777 --> 00:13:58.360
BEN FOLDS: OK.

00:13:58.360 --> 00:13:58.780
LAURA MURPHY: Seemingly--

00:13:58.780 --> 00:13:59.270
BEN FOLDS: Something
else besides--

00:13:59.270 --> 00:13:59.690
LAURA MURPHY: --that you love.

00:13:59.690 --> 00:14:00.970
BEN FOLDS: --besides
digital media.

00:14:00.970 --> 00:14:02.470
LAURA MURPHY: Besides
digital media.

00:14:02.470 --> 00:14:03.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:03.460 --> 00:14:03.960
Photography.

00:14:03.960 --> 00:14:04.585
BEN FOLDS: Yes.

00:14:04.585 --> 00:14:06.990
LAURA MURPHY: So, if you guys
haven't checked this out,

00:14:06.990 --> 00:14:10.370
Ben has one of the most
amazing photography sites.

00:14:10.370 --> 00:14:12.530
It's a split between
his music career

00:14:12.530 --> 00:14:15.410
and his photography,
where he is actually

00:14:15.410 --> 00:14:17.990
selling a lot of his work.

00:14:17.990 --> 00:14:19.800
A lot of his work
is highlighted.

00:14:19.800 --> 00:14:22.884
So we wanted to just kind of
ask you about a couple of these.

00:14:22.884 --> 00:14:24.800
I understand those might
be your own children?

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:25.190
BEN FOLDS: That's them.

00:14:25.190 --> 00:14:25.450
LAURA MURPHY: Is that right?

00:14:25.450 --> 00:14:26.490
BEN FOLDS: Would
you run it back one?

00:14:26.490 --> 00:14:27.448
LAURA MURPHY: Oh, sure.

00:14:27.448 --> 00:14:28.176
Of course.

00:14:28.176 --> 00:14:30.050
BEN FOLDS: Anyone know
the movie, "The Room?"

00:14:30.050 --> 00:14:30.644
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:14:30.644 --> 00:14:32.310
BEN FOLDS: Like, you
know, Tommy Wiseau?

00:14:32.310 --> 00:14:33.680
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

